On Wed, Mar 18, 2009 at 2:19 PM, Eric J. Bowman &lt;eric@...&gt;wrote:

&gt; Assaf Arkin wrote:
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; From an engineering standpoint I would recommend and use POST because
&gt; &gt; it&#39;s more explicit and clear.
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; Agreed.  Like I said in another thread, just write an HTML form and a
&gt; POST handler to do &quot;batch&quot; deletions.  So long as it&#39;s understood that
&gt; this has nothing to do with a uniform interface.  In REST, the
&gt; semantics assigned to DELETE are not also duplicated in POST --
&gt; deletion of resources has one and only one method.  POST is usually
&gt; being used to accept data, making it sometimes mean delete makes the
&gt; semantics of POST clear as mud.
&gt;

That&#39;s not what I understood. What I understood is: if you ask the server to
do some operation, and it tells you which URL to POST to (say via form), and
use POST as HTTP intended it to be used, then you&#39;re following the uniform
interface.

The server may tell you to use DELETE instead, which has different, and
possibly better semantics, and following those would also be part of the
uniform interface. But it&#39;s up to the server to decide which method it
prefers -- as long as the semantics are obeyed -- it&#39;s applying a uniform
interface.

Assaf



&gt;
&gt;
&gt; -Eric
&gt;

--000e0cd104fe8120d604656b539a
